Detection of outliers using the IQR (Interquartile range) method

Outlier #1 - LotArea

In [69]:
lot_area_p0 = df.LotArea.min()
lot_area_p100 = df.LotArea.max()
lot_area_q1 = df.LotArea.quantile(0.25)
lot_area_q2 = df.LotArea.quantile(0.5)
lot_area_q3 = df.LotArea.quantile(0.75)
lot_area_iqr = lot_area_q3 - lot_area_q1
In [70]:
lot_area_lc = lot_area_q1 - 1.5 * lot_area_iqr  # lower cutoff
lot_area_uc = lot_area_q3 + 1.5 * lot_area_iqr  # upper cutoff
In [71]:
lot_area_lc
Out[71]:
1481.5
In [72]:
lot_area_uc
Out[72]:
17673.5
In [73]:
print(f"LotArea: p0 = {lot_area_p0}, p100 = {lot_area_p100}, lc = {lot_area_lc}, uc = {lot_area_uc}")

LotArea: p0 = 1300, p100 = 215245, lc = 1481.5, uc = 17673.5

If lc < p0 There are NO outliers on the bottom side If uc > p100 There are NO outliers on the higher side

lc > p0, so there are outliers on the bottom side (1481.5 < 1300). uc < p100 (17673.5 < 215245), so there are also outliers on the higher side. A visual representation of an outlier is provided by a box plot

In [74]:

Outlier #1 - LotArea - treatment

In [75]:

df.LotArea.plot(kind='box')
